UNDIAGNOSED DEATHS - INDIA (UTTAR PRADESH) (02)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Sponsored in part by Elsevier, publisher of
The Lancet Infectious Diseases
<http://thelancet.url123.com/a5k35>
Date: Mon, 14 Nov 2005 12:28:38 +0530
From: T Jacob John <vlr_tjjohn@sancharnet.in>

I am responding to the request for more information by the moderator on the
report of undiagnosed deaths in India (Uttar Pradesh) -- 13 Nov 2005.
In the write-up the "ecovirus" is almost certainly echovirus, as suggested
by the moderator. The "cocktail virus" could either be coxsackievirus or
evidence of infection with more than one virus -- mostly serological, not
necessarily quality-controlled, and likely to be not very useful
information. Finding malarial parasites points to 2 questions -- (1) could
such children have had cerebral malaria? and (2) why is speciation between
_P. falciparum_ and _P. vivax_ not clarified? If that is not done, what
confidence can we have in a medical diagnosis?
The "self-culture system" mentioned in the last paragraph is most certainly
a cell culture system. NICD (National Institute of Communicable Diseases)
in New Delhi (or rather Old Delhi, to be accurate), has excellent cell
culture laboratories.
What I know -- from keeping watch over news and journal articles as well as
speaking with local pediatricians -- includes:
1. In the absence of fairly strict clinical (let alone laboratory) criteria
of syndromic diagnosis, do not assume that all cases suspected of being the
"mystery disease" are not cases of other diagnosable diseases such as
septicemia, cerebral malaria, typhoid encephalopathy, meningitis, viral
encephalitis, Reye's syndrome, other forms of toxic encephalopathies,
chemical/insecticide poisoning etc. When clinicians have been discerning,
they have found an undiagnosed illness with stereotypical clinical picture
(more below).
2. The typical case is an acute neurological catastrophic illness, with
very high case fatality -- over 50 per cent, usually 60-80 per cent. The
illness is very short -- death or recovery within a few days. Intravenous
mannitol to reduce brain edema is life-saving in many children. Case
fatality can be halved by this treatment alone.
4. The geographic distribution is fairly wide -- Western UP, nearby
Haryana, central India in some years, occasionally Andhra Pradesh and
Maharashtra. The illness occurs almost annually in some places like in
western UP (Saharanpur, Ghaziabad). It is predominantly rural and
peri-urban -- also in town slums and "disadvantaged" habitats. The
distribution is wide -- a few cases per village over weeks. In some cases
siblings are affected. [for a good map of India with states, see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/india_pol01.jpg> or
<http://www.mapsofindia.com/states/index.html> - Mod.MPP]
5. Although "seasonal", season varies in different locations. In
Saharanpore-Ghaziabad and similar recurrent spots, the seasonality is more
predictable -- September, October. In other places, any time from April or
May until October.
6. The crucial differentiation between encephalitis and encephalopathy is
often not made. Since Japanese encephalitis (JE) is well known in India,
every outbreak (except the repetitive seasonal ones in specific places) is
first called JE and then as studies find no clear evidence of JE, revised
as viral encephalitis; if no viral infection can be found, then it is left
as a mystery virus or disease. Many doctors do not perform lumbar punctures
(LPs) in sick children even with obvious neurological illness -- I cannot
understand why -- but they say the families might blame the LP and doctor
for any subsequent complications, including death. Moreover, laboratory
support services are grossly inadequate. In my judgement and after careful
review of several pieces of evidence -- including those of a few LPs done
by good pediatricians -- the "mystery disease" is an acute encephalopathy
syndrome closely resembling Reye's syndrome (Ref 1), more likely to be
toxic or multifactorial -- viral infection being quite unlikely.
7. I had requested a friend and colleague in Saharanpore (Bijnor to be
specific) -- Dr Vipin Vashishtha -- to do specific investigations for
Reye's syndrome. Except for the consistent microvesicular fat inclusion
bodies in hepatocytes, most other features -- CSF (cerebrospinal fluid)
without pleocytosis, under pressure due to brain edema, high liver enzyme
levels, low blood sugar, etc. fit with a Reye's-like picture (ref 2); case
fatality 84 per cent and total duration of illness 48 hours or less.
8. There have been many virological studies on similar outbreaks, but in
all of them clinical criteria were vague and epidemiology virtually absent.
In 2 'published' outbreaks (Vadodara and Warangal), measles virus was
detected in CSF or serum and incriminated as the etiolgy of the illness
(ref 3). In one genuine Reye's syndrome outbreak (ref 4), measles virus was
also detected in CSF and declared the etiology (ref 5). However, I do not
find these studies to be completely reliable (ref 6). Curiously, in another
similar recent outbreak, Chandipura virus (Genus vesiculovirus, family
Rhabdoviridae) was declared by virologists as the etiology in a study of 55
children (ref 7). The odd thing is that the very same 55 children were
reported by neurologists to have ischemic brain lesions and encephalopathy
-- but no encephalitis (ref 8,9).
I need not say more, although I have more historic information. The disease
ought to be called Khan's syndrome, for his description was the first (ref
10). All my efforts to get all players together across the table have
consistently failed. My current suspicion is agriculture practice-related
chemical toxicity as the proximate cause of illness -- of the Reye's-like
syndrome with clinical and laboratory features, reminiscent of "Udorn
encephalopathy" (ref 11,12). The vasculitis-ischemic syndrome deserves more
attention and study. Proper epidemiological investigation of every outbreak
is sorely needed. They will certainly provide clues.
References.
1. John TJ. Outbreaks of killer brain disease: mystery or missed diagnosis?
Indian Pediatr 2003; 40: 863-9.
2.Vashishtha VM. Brief profile of epidemic of acute encephalopathy in
western Uttar Pradesh. Indian Pediatr 2003; 40: 920-2.
3. Shaikh NJ, Wairagkar NS, Reddy SV, et al. Acute encephalitis without
rash in Warangal, Andhra Pradesh and Vadodara, Gujarat, associated with
measles virus. J Assoc Physicians India. 2002; 50: 1198.
4. Ghosh D, Dhadwal D, Aggarwal A, et al. Investigation of an outbreak of
Reye's syndrome in northern region of India. Indian Pediatr 1999; 36:
1097-1106.
5. Wairagkar NS, Shaik NJ, Ratho RK et al. Isolation of measles virus from
cerebrospinal fluid of children with acute encephalopathy without rash.
Indian Pediatr 2002; 38: 589-95.
6. John TJ. Encephalopathy without rash, caused by measles virus? More
evidence is needed. Indian Pediatr 2003; 40: 589-93.
7. Rao BL, Basu A, Wairagkar NS, et al. A large outbreak of acute
encephalitis with high fatality rate in children in Andhra Pradesh, India,
in 2003, associated with Chandipura virus. Lancet 2004; 364: 869-74.
8. Rao PN, Kumar PA, Rao TA, et al. Role of Chandipura virus in an
"epidemic brain attack" in Andhra Pradesh, India. J Pediatr Neurol 2004; 2:
131-43.
9. John TJ. Chandipura virus, encephalitis and epidemic brain attack in
India. Lancet 2004; 364: 2175.
10. Khan N. Jamshedpur fever: a preliminary report. Indian J Med Sci 1954;
8: 597-9.
11. Bourgeois CH, Keskhamras N, Comer DS. Udorn encephalopthy. Fatal
cerebral edema and fatty degeneration of the viscera in Thai children. J
Med Accos Thailand 1969; 52: 554-9.
12. Olson LC, Bougeois CH, Keskhamras N. Encephalopthy and fatty
degeneration of the viscera in Thai children. Am J Dis Child 1970; 120: 1-7.
