[ProMED-mail would like to thank Dr T Jacob John for this very informative
discussion of the previous post "Undiagnosed deaths - India (Uttar
Pradesh): RFI," 20051113.3322. From the above description it appears there
is an encephalitis or encephalopathy that occurs annually in several
states, but there are also other illnesses being grouped into this
syndromic diagnosis, with the suspicion that further testing would have
established a definitive etiology for some of these cases. For a very good
discussion of these illnesses and the justifications for the suggestion
that these cases may be Reye's syndrome, see Dr T Jacob John's first
reference <http://www.indianpediatrics.net/sep2003/sep-863-869.htm>.
In addition, from Belay ED, et al (Reye's syndrome in the United States
from 1981 through 1997 N Engl J Med 1999 340: 1377-1382): "The CDC defines
a case of Reye's syndrome as one in which there is acute, noninflammatory
encephalopathy, manifested clinically by alterations in the level of
consciousness and documented, when such results are available, by the
measurement of 8 or fewer leukocytes per cubic millimeter of cerebrospinal
fluid or by the presence of cerebral edema without perivascular or
meningeal inflammation in histologic sections of the brain. The
encephalopathy must be associated with either fatty metamorphosis of the
liver, diagnosed by biopsy or at autopsy, or a tripling (or a greater
increase) in the levels of alanine aminotransferase, aspartate
aminotransferase, or ammonia in serum. There must, moreover, be no other
more reasonable explanation of the cerebral or hepatic abnormalities."
Dr T Jacob John raises the issues of the diagnostic challenges and
questions the conclusions on the etiology of prior outbreaks of
encephalitis-like illnesses. In keeping with the discussion of diagnostic
challenges in India, the list of prior ProMED-mail postings on selected
"undiagnosed/unknown illnesses" from India that might be classified as part
of the above syndrome are included below. Many more 'undiagnosed' or
'unknown' threads have been omitted.
Clearly there is the need for further studies (including good epidemiologic
data as well as strong laboratory support) to identify the etiology of
this/these outbreaks. - Mod.MPP
There is no clear evidence that these outbreaks are due to a single viral
agent, or even that a virus is involved. The ubiquity of some of the
viruses mentioned -- enteric viruses such as echoviruses and
coxsackieviruses (of which there a large number), and the vectorborne
Chandipura virus -- make them unlikely candidates. Likewise the extent and
periodicity of these outbreaks argue against rare sporadic events such as
overspill into the human population of bat-associated henipaviruses.
Environmental toxins cannot be excluded. Professor John has made the point
that the aggregate data do not allow a specific diagnosis. Nonetheless his
analysis of the possibilities is very useful and intriguing. - Mod.CP]
